- volume drivers allow to abstract the underlying storage system from application logic. For example, services that use a volume with an NFS driver can be seamlessly updated to use a different driver (e.g. to store data in the cloud), without changing their application logic.

- you can specify a volume driver at creation time

- using the vieux/sshfs driver to connect to another node using ssh. 

    # As with other ssh clients, the password can be omitted if you have a key.
    $ docker volume create --driver vieux/sshfs \
        -o sshcmd=test@node2:/home/test \
        -o password=testpassword \
        sshvolume

- create a service which creates an NFSV3 volume

    # note that the volume driver specified is "local"
    $ docker service create -d \
        --name nfs-service \
        --mount 'type=volume,volume-driver=local,source=nfsvolume,target=/app,volume-opt=type=nfs,volume-opt=device=:/var/docker-nfs,volume-opt=o=addr=10.0.0.10' \
        nginx

- create a service which creates an NFSV4 volume

    # note how the last volume options are captured inside double quotes 
    $ docker service create -d \
        --name nfs-service \
        --mount 'type=volume,volume-driver=local,source=nfsvolume4,target=/app,volume-opt=type=nfs,volume-opt=device=:/,"volume-opt=o=10.0.0.10,rw,nfservers=4,async"' \
        nginx


